Very simply, we were attempting to create an overly complicated tool that would allow person A to match with person B based off of context and interest, at a local coffee shop or restaurant. name: Rachael Flores
about: Rachael Flores is an experienced independent school educator and administrator for over fifteen years. As the current Head of Upper School at The Spence School in New York, NY, Rachael previously led the work of diversity, equity, and inclusion for schools in the Washington, D.C. area for over ten years. In that work, Rachael oversaw strategic initiatives related to building and sustaining inclusive and equitable institutions through designing professional development, providing opportunities for community discourse, and serving as a critical resource for students, faculty/staff, and administrators. In addition to her work in schools, Rachael presents nationally. She currently sits on the National Partnership for Educational Access (NPEA) Advisory Board, previously served on the Mid-Atlantic Episcopal School Association (MAESA) Board of Governors, The Association of Independent Schools of Greater Washington (AISGW)’s Diversity, Equity, and Inclusion Task Force, and has led workshops for the Independent School Management’s (ISM) Summer Institutes. Rachael’s training through the National SEED Project and work as a faculty member of the National Association of Independent School's Student Diversity Leadership Conference (SDLC) since 2013 prepared her to facilitate a wide range of topics related to identity, equity and systems of oppression. Rachael holds degrees from Princeton University (BA, History), George Washington University (M.A., History), and is a doctoral candidate in the Executive Leadership Program on Human and Organizational Learning at George Washington University in Washington DC. Her dissertation will examine the intersection of inclusion, identity, and well-being among working engineers in the United States.

name: Diego Solorio
about: Astrophysics. As the toddler who created water vortexes with the salad spinner instead of playing with actual toys, understanding the underlying mechanics of the universe always dominated my heart.  Besides being involved in STEM clubs such as MESA or Quiz Bowl during my high school career, I pushed beyond what was offered to pursue my passion and was accepted into two astrophysics summer programs: UCI’s COSMOS and UC Berkeley’s ATDP, eye-opening programs that further fueled my fire for physics.  I also had the unbelievable opportunity to intern at NASA’s Jet Propulsion Laboratory, where I worked on an astrophysics-based computer science project, which remains disclosed.  My heart and soul are all in for astrophysics.Other than my passion for the science field, I am a leader.  Formerly, I was a shy turtle who had nightmares about group work and presentations.  I have since realized that a true scientist would need to be able to communicate their findings effectively and work well with groups.  Over lots of blood sweat and tears, I have been able to metamorphosis into a social butterfly!  I was elected as the Lieutenant Governor of Division 4 West Key Club, where I ran a 27-person board and gave speeches and hosted service events on the regular.  Through Key Club and ASB, I have experience in leading and working with groups as a benevolent and encouraging voice.

The Lab will collect, clean, geocode, aggregate, and publicize the results of debt collection court cases that rendered judgments between 2017 and 2018. A future data collection effort will gather this data from 2021 and 2022, before and after the global pandemic that is likely to push more families into debt.

Our project is to empower debtors through knowledge of their financial options, to inform them of their rights and legal resources, and to close the communication gap in debt collection. We aim to make these processes fairer and more manageable for the debtor and the creditor, envisioning that the functional and emotional needs of both parties are met.

Based on Bown & Crowley (2007), we investigate the existence and magnitude of a deflection effect of US trade barriers on EU imports in a context of heightened uncertainty in global trade. Using dynamic panel data, we assess the impact of changes in US trade defence policy against third country exporters on the volume of EU imports using antidumping data from Bown (2015). We find evidence of a significant 8-22% increase on average in the volume of EU imports of targeted goods.

One-Shot Learning using RRAM-Based Associative Memory

Real-time learning from a few examples (one/few-shot learning) is a key challenge for machine learning systems today. When never-seen-before data is encountered, conventional parametric models like DNNs need to re-learn their parameters via gradient-based learning, often requiring huge amount of data coupled with slow learning iterations. Non-parametric models (like nearest neighbours) do not require any training, but have lower accuracy. Recent research has combined the two to create “memory-augmented” neural networks (MANNs) that can rapidly learn new examples while still performing well on common examples. MANNs consist of a frontend, which is a traditional CNN or RNN, that extracts features from new classes, and a backend associative memory that stores a hashed version of these features. During learning, new features are stored in the memory, and during inference, the feature computed on input data is compared with all the features stored in the memory, and the closest match determines the classification result. This work implements an associative memory with an RRAM-based content addressable memory for area-efficient feature storage and fast feature matching.

name: William Coulton
about: Since 2013 I have been a graduate student at Princeton University studying cosmology, where my research is focused on the interface between theory and data. In particular, I develop physical models and statistical tools to compare them with data.  I have primarily worked on modelling and measuring non-Gaussian signals in the cosmic microwave background. In addition, I have worked on modeling distortions in the HSC CCDs.During these projects I have become involved with two collaborations: the Hyper-suprime camera collaboration, focused on an optical camera on the Subaru telescope in Hawaii, and the Atacama Cosmology Telescope collaboration, a microwave telescope in Chile. My experience in these collaborations has helped me grow as team player and developed my technical communications skills.Through my research I have developed strong python skills as well as a working knowledge of C++ and Fortran. My research particularly benefited from my knowledge of high performance computing. In parallel to my research, I have furthered my interest in machine learning methods.

Utilizing data from the recent MassiveBlack and MassiveBlack-II  hydrodynamical simulations, I investigated a range of properties of high redshift galaxies from their luminosity and mass functions to their UV continuum slopes. Finally I performed a small analysis of the effect of cosmic variance on measurements of Hubble sized volumes.

name: Lara Buchak
about: I am an Professor in the Department of Philosophy at Princeton.  I received my Ph.D. in Philosophy from Princeton in 2009, and was a professor at UC Berkeley for 12 years.My primary research interests are in decision, game, and rational choice theory. My book Risk and Rationality (Oxford University Press, 2013) concerns how an individual ought to take risk into account when making decisions. It vindicates the ordinary decision-maker from the point of view of even ideal rationality. I also have research interests in the philosophy of religion and in epistemology. Some topics I have written on include the relationship between assigning probability to a hypothesis and believing that hypothesis outright; the conditions under which one ought to stop looking for more evidence and make a decision; when and why social equality matters; and the nature of faith, both in the religious and the more mundane sense.Website: www.larabuchak.net

Jun 2010 - Aug 2010 · 3 mos
I interned with Dr. Richard Steiner on the Electronic Kilogram project.  The Electronic Kilogram project research centered around the Watt Balance.  The Watt Balance is a super precise and accurate weighing machine which exactly offsets the force of gravity pulling on an object by a force produced when an electrical current is run through a coil of wire in a magnetic field.  The Watt Balance provides a basis for a new definition of the base quantity mass, based on invariant quantum properties of nature.  The kilogram is the only SI unit that is still defined by an artifact (a platinum iridium mass which is unfortunately unstable).

My role was to measure the gravitational acceleration constant in the immediate area around the Watt Balance (which was in the process of moving to a new building), and assembling a map based on my measurements of the gravitational field.  In doing so, I had to correct for many phenomenon, such as the tides and building vibrations.

http://www.nist.gov/pml/div684/grp05/kilogram.cfm

name: Camila Llerena-Olivera
about: Hello! My name is Camila. I am a PhD candidate in the Civil and Environmental Engineering department at Princeton University. I completed my bachelor's and master's degrees in Environmental and Ecological Engineering at Purdue University. My diverse experience in environmental research has given me a multidimensional perspective on issues such as water quality, social sustainability, biorenewable energy, and waste reduction. With my internship at the Indiana Department of Environment Management, I jumpstarted the largest PFAS (per- and polyfluroalkyl substances) investigation in the State of Indiana. I've also led many research projects at Purdue that have helped me develop my critical thinking skills and impacted stakeholders such as small villages and pharmaceutical companies. During my free time, I enjoy supporting minority students with their paths toward advanced education. Through the Purdue Minority Engineering Program, I served as an ambassador for over 4 years to educate and recruit underrepresented minority students into Purdue's engineering program. As the 2017-2018 president of the Purdue Chapter of Latinos in Science and Engineering (MAES), I led over 50 active members in our professional development and cultural enrichment programs.

People in the outskirts of Arequipa, Peru have been falling ill due to metal contamination from river water. Under the guidance of Dr. Chad Javert (Environmental Engineering), I researched different aspects of this water quality project. I first investigated the locations of watersheds to sample water in Arequipa. I looked at Peruvian government and NGO databases to find potential sampling locations. I mapped out over 30 locations with Google Earth Pro. My first map was used in a field survey by Purdue researchers in March. I then assisted in finding parts for a watershed monitoring system and UV LED water sanitation system.

Indianapolis, Indiana
During the summer, I worked in the Office of Land Quality on research related to PFAS (per- and polyfluoroalkyl substances). PFAS are a set of emerging contaminants that can cause long-term health effects such as disruption of endocrine activity, cancer, and birth defects. PFAS are used for nonstick and waterproof applications. They can be found in food packaging, clothing, and other daily necessities. My task for this project was to find potential sites for the largest PFAS investigation in the State of Indiana. I presented my findings in a 250 page report that will be sent to the commissioner of IDEM.

I have a personal connection to this project since most of my family in my paternal side lives in Arequipa. Research Assistant at the Laboratory for Sustainable Manufacturing
Aug 2018 · 1 mo
A graduate student advised by Dr. John Sutherland (Environmental Engineering) needed assistance on his project related to social sustainability. This field of research is related to understanding how sustainability in the workplace can promote the overall well-being of stakeholders.  Three sets of surveys were given to people associated with anonymous companies. Each survey had questions related to the basic, safety, affiliation, esteem, and actualization needs that the stakeholder groups could deem necessary. The necessity of each need was scaled from 1-5, with 1 being not important and 5 being very important. My task for this month-long project was to create 30 tables from these sets of questions. The tables improved the organization of these questions and presentation of the student's paper.
Laboratory for Sustainable Manufacturing (LSM)
The LSM focuses on all three pillars of sustainability: environmental, social, and economic. Areas of research include smart/sustainable manufacturing, circular materials economy, green manufacturing planning, social sustainability of manufacturing, and sustainability impacts.

Jun 2016 - May 2018 · 2 yrs
A visiting graduate student working with Dr. Walter Daniel Leon-Salas (Electrical Engineering Technology) built a microwave station with materials under $500 for his thesis. The student left Purdue University after completing his thesis. He did not have enough time to test the station, ultimately leaving his research incomplete. Under the guidance of Dr. Michael Harris (Chemical Engineering), I investigated how well the station worked compared to other expensive stations on the market. The experiment included the following work: revising the initial procedure, preparing standards of cellulose powder with varying moisture contents, recording data from the standards with vnaJ software, graphing results with MATLAB, and analyzing electrical parameter shifts. During the first three weeks of my research, I also supervised a high school intern participating in this project.

Cook Research Incorporated
Jan 2018 - May 2018 · 5 mos
Senior design is a capstone project required for undergraduates in Environmental and Ecological Engineering. Each team is partnered with a company to solve an environmental problem. My team was partnered with Cook Research Incorporated (CRI), a subsidiary of the medical device company Cook Medical. The purpose of this project was to to characterize the waste streams of the CRI building and to propose a plan to improve their current recycling system. To accomplish this task, the team submitted a waste sampling plan to the president of CRI, sampled 1/3 of the waste in the recycling/non-recycling dumpsters by weight at various days, and presented the results to CRI employees at a monthly company meeting.
Identification of Waste Streams at Cook Research Incorporated to Decrease Overall Waste
The goal for students is to decrease the overall landfill waste and identify areas where recycling or reuse could be more effective. Additionally, there are five other Cook companies in West Lafayette who could incorporate waste stream changes, making the overall impact much larger than a single company.

I was elected as the Purdue Chapter president of MAES- Latinos in Science and Engineering for the 2017-2018. MAES is a national organization with over 40 collegiate and professional chapters. As president of one of the largest STEM minority organizations on campus, I oversaw 50 active members in the chapter’s professional networking and cultural enrichment programs. During my presidency, my primary goals were to focus on recruitment/retention rates and broaden the chapter's professional network. I created a leadership development program to increase retention rates of new members from 30% to 85%. I was also able to partner with businesses for workshops related to resume reviews, mock interviews, and informal dinners. In addition,  I introduced a graduate workshop set up by the Minority Engineering Program and had a handful of MAES members to attend a GEM (Graduate Engineering Minority) Fellowship conference in Chicago. The chapter also won the collegiate Region 3 award in 2017 at our national conference in California.

experience:

Graduate Program in Plasma Physics, Department of Astrophysical Sciences
Research Assistant
University of Illinois at Urbana-Champaign
Aug 2015 - Sep 2018 · 3 yrs 2 mos
Center for Plasma Material Interactions
Currently I am setting up a schlieren imaging system to characterize an atmospheric plasma jet used for industrial cleaning and activation of metallic surfaces. Schlieren is a powerful diagnostic that allows imaging of density variations in a refractive medium.

During my junior year (Fall 2016 - Spring 2017), I investigated the feasibility and engineering parameters of small compact toroid devices with computational and mathematical methods, under the guidance of Professor Davide Curreli. Specifically, I am exploring spheromaks with extremely compact geometries, tending towards a flux conserver radius of roughly 5 cm. 

In terms of hands on experience with fusion research, my work at the Center for Plasma Material Interactions (CPMI), under the guidance of Professor David Ruzic and Professor Daniel Andruczyk, has given me valuable practical knowledge in the design of laboratory plasma experiments. I have worked on the setup and data acquisition of several projects at CPMI, including the Hybrid Illinois Device for Research Applications (HIDRA), and the DEVeX theta pinch device. With the HIDRA fusion device, I have helped install the electrical and cooling systems so that the device can commence experiments on flowing liquid lithium plasma facing components (PFCs). I have also prepared a 6kW magnetron heating source for plasma heating experiments in HIDRA. With DEVeX, over this past summer I worked with a visiting scientist from Princeton Plasma Physics Lab (PPPL) to study a novel plasma facing component (porous Moly wetted with Lithium) in the presence of a plasma instability. This type of PFC will be studied further at PPPL in NSTX-U, the National Spherical Tokamak Experiment.

name: Jimmy (Tsung-Yen) Yang
about: I am a final year graduate student in the Department of Electrical and Computer Engineering at Princeton University, working with Prof. Peter Ramadge and Prof. Karthik Narasimhan, since September 2017.My research interests lie at the intersection of machine learning, control theory, safe reinforcement learning (safe RL), and natural language processing (NLP). My work has been published and presented in leading machine learning venues, including NeurIPS, ICML, ICLR, and EMNLP. Specifically, I have been working on machine learning projects, including but not limited to(1) Reinforcement learning with safety constraints for self-driving cars;(2) Control of robotic systems;(3) Anomaly detection from sensor measurements;(4) Instruction following in natural language processing;(5) Simulation to real transfer using physics priors and transformers;(6) Representation learning from user behavioral data.Before Princeton, I received my BS in Electrical Engineering and Computer Science (Honors Program) at National Chiao Tung University, Taiwan.

Reinforcement Learning (RL)
1. Develop a constrained RL algorithm that optimizes rewards while satisfying safety constraints with statistical learning bounds for the worst-case constraint violations.
2. Improve sample-efficiency of an RL algorithm by incorporating baseline policies from prior applications.
3. Deploy the constrained RL algorithm in real-world applications ranging from controlling a traffic flow, planning safe trajectories for autonomous vehicles, and safely learning from human demonstrations.
4. Execute the proposed algorithm, which achieves up to 10 times faster learning efficiency while ensuring safety constraint satisfaction during learning.
5. Integrate deep learning models with physics priors to improve the sample efficiency of the model.

Natural Language Processing (NLP)
1. Develop a learning algorithm and computational model to learn a control policy for instruction-following tasks and achieve state-of-the-art performance.
2. Propose a model that uses natural language to specify a set of constraints observed by robotic systems.

name: Monica Patino
about: When I began the spring semester of my sophomore year in 2020, I had no idea how dramatically my college experience would change once the COVID-19 cases began to skyrocket in the United States. Like many students across the country, I was sent to complete the semester back at home. I was able to experience firsthand how debilitating the virus was for my community, which is mostly composed of Hispanic and low-income families. Although I had already decided to major in Chemical and Biological Engineering (CBE), I was unsure of which of the six CBE concentrations I would pursue. Living through a pandemic and seeing how the whole world was affected inspired me to choose to concentrate on Bioengineering and Biotechnology.During my junior year, I took two courses that really drove my interest in drug development: Molecular and Cellular Immunology and Antibiotics: From Cradle to Grave. Through taking Molecular and Cellular Immunology, I learned about how the immune system responds and provides a defense mechanism against microorganisms using cellular and molecular mechanisms, and how understanding these mechanisms is critical in the development of vaccines and forms of immunotherapy, especially during the development of COVID-19 vaccines. As this course taught the very technical sides of immunology, Antibiotics: From Cradle to Grave taught me how science, engineering, medicine, and policy have shaped the current age of antibiotics. We went from discussing the development of antibiotics and the benefits that they brought to the world to how the overuse of them both in humans and animals is driving the promotion of antibiotic resistance. These two courses really drove my interest in drug development and inspired my senior thesis topic. During my senior year, I joined the Link Lab, where I worked on my thesis research, focusing on the stability and activity of a novel lasso peptides research, which is important to study given their wide variety of biological functions, such as their antimicrobial and antiviral activity, anti-HIV activity, receptor antagonism activity, and enzyme inhibition activity.As the pandemic persists, I desire to pursue opportunities in bioengineering and biotechnology that will allow me to contribute to the efforts currently being made to develop treatments for illnesses that affect millions of people across the world.

name: Marissa Mejia
about: As a student pursuing a concentration in Psychology and a certificate in Environmental Studies at Princeton University, I am particularly interested in the intersections between human cognition and behavior when it comes to sustainable actions. The climate crisis is the most pressing issue of my generation’s time, and I hope to contribute to its solutions in whatever capacity I can. This love of environmentalism overlaps with my interest in social justice as the two are inextricably intertwined through environmental justice, and I hope to employ my knowledge of, experience with, and passion for these fields in my future career.
experience:
Princeton University
Part-time · 2 yrs 4 mos
Princeton, New Jersey, United States
Residential College Advisor
Aug 2021 - Present · 9 mos
As a Residential College Advisor (RCA) in Princeton University's Mathey College, I foster an inclusive and engaging community for undergraduate students by promoting safety, civic responsibility, and wellness. I strive to maintain an environment in which all members of Princeton’s diverse campus community feel comfortable, and I do so by hosting weekly study breaks, study halls, and dinners for a group of first-year advisees in order to create this sense of community and help them transition to life as Princeton students. I meet with each of my zees in one-on-one meetings to develop personal connections with them and ensure that I am supporting them in ways that are most valuable to them, and I also train extensively with the residential college staff and members of university offices to learn how to best address wellness concerns, drug and alcohol use, interpersonal conflicts, and struggles with academics or social adjustments.
EcoRep Social Media Leader
Jan 2020 - Present · 2 yrs 4 mos
As a member of the Ecology Representative Program (EcoReps) Social Media Team, I promote sustainability among 2800+ Instagram followers through curating post content for the Office of Sustainability’s Instagram (@tigersgogreen). I have spearheaded multiple initiatives that promote the adoption of sustainable habits, highlight our EcoReps leaders, raise awareness of environmental dilemmas, encourage voting for a green future, and more. I often collaborate with staff from other university offices to highlight environmentalism’s intersection with social justice, and I have designed many interactive posts that have been reposted and replicated by dozens of university offices across the nation.
Summer Intern
Ka Honua Momona International · Internship
May 2021 - Aug 2021 · 4 mos
Moloka'i, Hawai'i, United States
Throughout the summer of 2021, I was incredibly fortunate to be able to intern at Ka Honua Momona International, a Native Hawaiian environmental conservation nonprofit organization located on the small island of Moloka'i in Hawai'i. Through this position, I was able to work very closely with the island's kupuna (wise elders) and ecosystems to contribute to Indigenous environmental and cultural conservation efforts. I have listed some of my favorite initiatives below:
• Monitoring the health of Moloka'i's coral reef & limu (seaweed) populations, planting native species, and aiding in the removal of 5000+ pounds of invasive species
• Redesigning kahonuamomona.org for desktop, tablet, & mobile formats to make the site more user-friendly & aesthetic
• Initiating Ka Honua Momona's Āhā’ilono, or newsletter, which provides monthly updates and encourages involvement and donations
• Directing, filming, and producing ‘Ike Kūhohonu, a documentary featuring Moloka’i’s Indigenous elders and their memories of, experiences with, and hopes for the future of ancient Hawaiian fishponds
Communications Intern
Land to Learn · Internship
Jun 2020 - Jan 2021 · 8 mos
New York Hudson Valley
Throughout the summer of 2020 as well as between the Fall 2020 and Spring 2021 semesters, I had the wonderful opportunity of interning with Land to Learn, a small nonprofit based in the New York Hudson Valley that aims to grow a movement for food justice and community wellness through implementing interdisciplinary garden-based education programs in public schools. I worked closely with Land to Learn’s communications, marketing, and public relations employees to coordinate and publicize initiatives that reach out to the largely underprivileged communities that Land to Learn works with. I have listed some of my favorite initiatives and accomplishments below:

 •  Compiled & designed guides for free meals in NY during COVID that cumulatively impacted 6,600+ Facebook users
 •  Increased Facebook viewership by 902% (6733 people) and engagement by 730% (1,120 people)
 •  Advised LtL staff on fundraising platforms and marketing strategies to use when running a Peer-to-Peer Fundraiser
 •  Created promotional content for fundraiser, which provided ~1500 students with at-home garden kits & virtual lessons
 •  Employed LtL’s social media platforms to highlight partner organizations & hardworking staff members during pandemic
 •  Designed flyers & infographics promoting economically-accessible, COVID-friendly virtual summer programs for children
